    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-07-27T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-07-27T13:00:00-05:00" n="706"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d706">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/1395</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at London</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SRP1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Skinner</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-07-27T18:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 27, 1915, 6 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 3.40 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Department’s 23d [22d].<note n="2" xml:id="d706fn2">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_484">p. 484</ref>.</note> On
                    going into effect order in council March 11, 28 cotton ships were seized up to
                    May 19. Few seizures since. These 28 ships carried 204,633 bales, of which 8,891
                    were <pb facs="0746" n="488" xml:id="pg_488"/> released. Practically all seized
                    cotton is being purchased under so-called cotton agreement, and where proofs
                    adequate, advance ten cents per pound made without difficulty, final adjustment
                    on ascertainment weights and qualities. Some few lots in the total held for
                    prize court as having been sold to Germans, although said lots were forwarded on
                    in cotton agreement.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SRP1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Skinner</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
